{
  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "Especially given that LLMs are tools that primarily impact knowledge work, we argue that they are likely to have differential impacts on these innovation types.",
    "Iterative innovation-which benefits from detailed context and often has a clear \"right answer\" or a clearly defined evaluation metric (e.g., drug repurposing or recommender system)-is likely to be settings where humans will incorporate LLM solutions.",
    "Capability innovation, however, involve inherently open-ended or ambiguous contexts and may not have a set of \"right answers\" (e.g., evaluating the benefits of gene editing technologies), potentially making contributors less likely to rely exclusively on LLMs for these tasks.",
    "This intuition is further supported by two key observations: (a) most AI systems are evaluated on tasks with well-defined solutions rather than open-ended exploration, and (b) LLMs predict the most likely response to an input sequence based on their exposure to vast amounts of text, resulting in outputs that reflect established patterns and solutions (Brown et al. 2020).",
    "Extant research on LLMs has primarily examined controlled experimental settings (Brynjolfsson et al. 2025; Boussioux et al., 2024; Chen and Chan, 2024; Doshi and Houser 2024; Doshi et al. 2024), empirical studies on individual contributors (Zhou and Lee, 2024), or user-generated content platforms (Quinn and Gutt, 2023; Burtch et al., 2024), which all differ fundamentally from collaborative development."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "This intuition is further supported by two key observations: (a) most AI systems are evaluated on tasks with well-defined solutions rather than open-ended exploration, and (b) LLMs predict the most likely response to an input sequence based on their exposure to vast amounts of text, resulting in outputs that reflect established patterns and solutions (Brown et al. 2020).",
    "Extant research on LLMs has primarily examined controlled experimental settings (Brynjolfsson et al. 2025; Boussioux et al., 2024; Chen and Chan, 2024; Doshi and Houser 2024; Doshi et al. 2024), empirical studies on individual contributors (Zhou and Lee, 2024), or user-generated content platforms (Quinn and Gutt, 2023; Burtch et al., 2024), which all differ fundamentally from collaborative development."
  ]
}